   <abstract>Rising partisan prejudice in the U.S. has rendered relations between the two political sides increasingly volatile. Meanwhile, an uncivil and hyper-partisan political climate has likely fomented social tolerance for, and even approval of, hostile expressions toward members of the political outgroup. The present work first reports preliminary evidence that the desire to politically aggress is strongly related to approval-seeking motivation to express political hostility (Study 1). Initial findings suggest that approval-seeking motivation predicts the desire to politically aggress above and beyond mere perceptions of ingroup support for political hostility, personal approval of political hostility, and other key variables (e.g., trait aggression). An experiment then measured political aggression behaviorally (i.e., with a noise blast task; Study 2). Participants played a reaction time game, during which they were given the opportunity to aggress against a political outgroup opponent in the presence of an ostensible spectator who was presented as either a political ingroup member (experimental) or neutral (control) spectator. Participants high (compared to low) in approval-seeking motivation were predicted to display greater levels of aggression toward the outgroup opponent when they thought a fellow ingroup member was watching. Results indicated, however, that Republican/Right-leaning participants showed more aggression in the ingroup spectator (compared to the control) condition. The same pattern did not emerge for Democratic/Left-leaning participants, who displayed lower levels of aggression overall. Findings suggest political aggression is a complex phenomenon and its findings may vary across time and behavior.</abstract>
